{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537211"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15960"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15960"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.2,0.19,0.5,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8651"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85636"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"3854"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"8011"},{"type":"tags","id":"11637"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a two day history of swelling under her tongue. It is slightly uncomfortable, but she does not experience any increased pain when eating. She smokes 1 cigarette/day, has a glass of wine on most nights but is otherwise well with no regular medications. On examination, this swelling is noted on the floor of the mouth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral cancer","Siliadentitis","Odontogenic cyst","Ranula","Palatal cyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eranula\u003C/strong\u003E, a benign fluid-filled cyst which presents along the salivary duct lines of the floor of the mouth. It is a subset of mucoceles; ranulas are located on the floor of the mouth and mucoceles are commonly seen on the inner lip surfaces. Trauma to the salivary glands, or chronic inflammation from smoking or other irritants can precipitate mucocele and ranula formation. They generally appear rapidly, spontaneously rupture and resolve within days. Recurrent cases may require referral to an oral surgeon for excision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile smoking is a risk factor for\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eoral cancer\u003C/strong\u003E, the appearance and timeline of the lesion in this case is inconsistent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialadenitis\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0involves salivary gland blockage by a calculi or stone. This is generally associated with dry mouth, pain with eating, and swelling of the affected gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOdontogenic cysts\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eoccur at the site of teeth which have not yet erupted and most commonly noticed on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalatal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Epstein pearls are small benign cysts of the hard palate of infants and usually resolve spontaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ranulas are mucoceles which occur along the salivary duct lines of the floor of the mouth.","Trauma and chronic inflammation of salivary ducts can precipitate mucocele and ranula formation."],"references":["Huzaifa M, Soni A. Mucocele and Ranula. StatPearls Publishing. Updated July 24, 2023. Accessed November 20, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560855/","Wong T. Common benign and malignant oral mucosal disease. AJGP. 2020; 49(9)","Bova R. A guide to salivary gland disorders. Medicine Today. 2006; 7(2)","Wang L, Olmo H. Odontogenic cysts. StatPearls Publishing. Updated September 26, 2022. Accessed November 20, 2024. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574529/","Diaz de Ortiz, LE, Mendez MD. Palatal and Gingival Cysts of the Newborn. StatPearls Publishing. Updated March 24, 2023. Accessed November 20, 2024.. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493177/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85636"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15960"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21205"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21205"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ALqEFyCxM8lhZ0SCEzy69ARaDXd6aG.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ALqEFyCxM8lhZ0SCEzy69ARaDXd6aG.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1125,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85636"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T15:27:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T15:27:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8651"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103199"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount"